You are clearly trying to create a state machine, which is a fully supported thing to build in Verilog. Its just that they way you are coding is not the clearest way to do this, in terms of other people understanding your code, and also very important, the synthesis and implementation tools implementing precisely what you are seeking.

You ask if I would I be more precise about what is bad or ambiguous with they way the design is currently coded?  Sure. The statement @(posedge clk); used in line says to stop the execution of the current code until the clock goes from low to high, after the previous statements were executed.  In a simulator, or c program, it is posible to do this; you would suspend the process that is implementing that always block.  Further the tool would (some how) arrange that the code is no longer activated it when an event in the original sensitivity list &quot;always @(read or rst)&quot; occurs; but now resume the process when the event posedge clock occurs.  

For the synthesis tool to implement this, it would have to build logic that sometimes looks for read and rst, and other times looks for a change of clock from 0 to 1; and keep track of when to do which activity. Or restated, it would have to create a state machine to implement your coding style (which is then creating another state machine!). While all things are possible, a tradeoff was made.

The original authors of synthesis tools met with the original coders of Verilog simulators and designers of logic and worked out a deal (IEEE Std 1364.1 - Verilog Register Transfer Level Synthesis) to define what constructs would be easy for humans to code, efficient for the simulators to execute, and straightforward for the synthesis tools to build logic that executed exactly the way the simulators executed.

Following this lead, it is far better for you to describe the state machine you want in a way that has clear hardware implementation methodology.

A state machine has construct that maintains a register that hold the value of the current state, and then separately logic that calculates the value of the next state, based on the current state, and the inputs to the module.  (See Mealy machine in the literature, such as Wikipedia, alternatively see the Moore Machine)

Based on looking at your code, a typical Mealy state machine would be:

    module sm (/*AUTOARG*/
       // Outputs
       data,
       // Inputs
       address, clk, read, rst
       ) ;
       input clk;
       input rst;
       input read;
       input [8:0] address
       output [31:0] data;
       reg [31:0] mem[256]
                  
       // State registers for state
       reg [2:0] state, next_state;
       parameter idle_state = 0, read_state = 1;
       
       // State FF for state
       always @ ( posedge clk or rst ) begin
          if ( rst ) state = idle_state; else
            state = next_state;
       end
    
       // Next State Logic for state
       always @ ( /*AUTOSENSE*/ /*memory or*/ addr_in or idle_state
                 or read or read_state or state) begin
          case (state) 
            idle_state: begin
               if (read) begin
                  address    = addr_in;
                  next_state = read_state;
               end
            end
            read_state: begin
               data = mem[address];
               next_state = idle_state;
            end
          endcase // case (cmd)
       end // always @ (...
    endmodule // sm

