The scope of &quot;`name`&quot; is the class &quot;`Test`&quot; not just method &quot;`function1()`&quot;.

So you can access &quot;`name`&quot; in &quot;`function1`&quot; and &quot;`function2`&quot; since their scope is also class &quot;`Test`&quot;.

It&#39;s even possible to access &quot;`name`&quot; from &quot;outside&quot;, since it&#39;s a public field. 

```
public class Test {

    public String name;

    public void function1() {
        this.name = &quot;F1&quot;;
    }

    public void function2() {
        this.name += &quot; F2&quot;;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return String.format(&quot;%s - &#39;%s&#39;&quot;, this.getClass().getSimpleName(), this.name);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test t = new Test();
        t.function1();
        System.out.println(&quot;1. - &quot; + t);
        t.function2();
        System.out.println(&quot;2. - &quot; + t);
        t.name = &quot;Hello World&quot;;
        System.out.println(&quot;3. - &quot; + t);
    }
}
```

BTW: 

- `function1()` and `function2()` are called &quot;`method`&quot; in java, since they are bound to a class. 
- &quot;`name`&quot; is a &quot;`class field`&quot; or short &quot;`field`&quot;.

Java doesn&#39;t technically support global variables. As a pure
object-oriented language, everything needs to be part of a class. The
reason is to protect data and members of classes from being changed,
inadvertently or on purpose, by other parts of the program. However,
