Java has 4 parameter scopes:

1) Class/static scope:  these are visible at the class level, denoted with the &#39;static keyword&#39;

2) Object/instance scope:  these are visible to a particular object, or instance of a class.  

3) Method scope:  these are visible within a particular method.

4) Block scope:  these are visible within a particular code block, e.g. an &#39;if&#39; block or &#39;for&#39; loop.

Example:

    public static class AClass {
      
      public static int CLASS_SCOPED = 0; // scoped to the class itself

      public int instanceScoped = 1; // scoped to a particular instance of the class

      public AClass(int instanceScoped) { 
        this.instanceScoped = instanceScoped;
      }

      public void someMethod() {
        int methodScoped = 2; // visible only within &#39;someMethod&#39; method

        while (returnSomeBoolean()) {
          int blockScoped = methodScoped+1; // visible only within enclosing &#39;while&#39; loop
        }
      } 


    }

